        "icon": "🎯",
        "title": "Three Days Is the Whole Assignment",
        "body": "Last cycle prescribed four days and got about sixty percent — including one stretch of ten days with nothing logged. So we redesigned around reality: three days, nothing wasted, conditioning folded in. That means the maths changed too — three of three is 100 percent, and there is no \"optional\" session anymore. Miss one and you've missed a third of the week. Put the three days in your calendar next to your padel sessions every Saturday, and treat them with the same respect you give a booked court."
      },
      {
        "icon": "📈",
        "title": "The Bar Goes Up on Schedule",
        "body": "Your squat sat at 20 kg for a month — and your last squat session was RPE 6, which tells me the plateau was the loading, not you. So this cycle the guesswork is gone: every primary lift has a written weekly target (squat +2.5 kg per week, hip thrust +5). When the session says add weight, add it — don't wait to \"feel ready\", because your logs prove you underestimate yourself. If a jump is genuinely above RPE 8, hold once and tell me in the report. That's the only exception."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🤔",
        "title": "One Question From Your Logs",
        "body": "On June 3rd you logged a 30 kg deadlift — then every session after went back to 20 and never returned. Either that was a real lift (in which case you're stronger than this programme assumed and we'll raise the targets), or it was a logging slip. Tell me in your next session report which one it was — one sentence is enough. Your logs are how I coach you between sessions, so this one number actually matters."
      },
      {
        "icon": "⚡",
        "title": "Fast Is a Skill, Not an Effort",
        "body": "This cycle adds jumps with fewer reps, continuous bounds, rotational slams, and push presses — and every one of them is graded on speed, not sweat. A slow throw is a wasted rep even if it's heavy; a crisp one at max intent is the whole point. If bar speed dies mid-set on the deadlift, stop the set — that's not quitting, that's power training done correctly. Your body learns whatever you repeat: repeat fast."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🍽️",
        "title": "The Six-Pack Is Still in the Kitchen",
        "body": "Nothing about the abs goal changed: a small daily calorie deficit plus around 130 g of protein, every day, is what makes the core work visible. The training side is covered — wood chops, hanging knee raises, carries, and the highest-intent conditioning yet. What I can't program is the plate. If the last cycle's nutrition drifted with the missed sessions, this is the reset: three trained days, seven fed-right days."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🎾",
        "title": "Space the Heavy Days",
        "body": "Day 1 and Day 3 are both heavy lower-body days — squat on one, deadlift and hip thrust on the other. One rule for arranging your week: never put them back-to-back. Slot padel or Day 2 between them, and your legs will be fresh enough to actually hit the weekly load targets. If a week goes sideways and only one session fits, do Day 1 — and remember the minimum that still counts: the first power move plus the first primary lift."
      },
      {
        "icon": "💥",
        "title": "The Finisher Is Your Third Set",
        "body": "The old conditioning day didn't survive contact with your calendar — you did it once — so its best weapon moved into Day 3: eight rounds of 20 seconds on, 40 off, at full intent. This is the exact energy demand of a long padel rally: explode, recover fast, explode again. Don't pace the early rounds to survive the late ones. It's eight minutes; empty the tank."
